{"slide1":"This presentation includes mentions of the Holocaust, which may be sensitive to some viewers. Anne Frank's diary text has been edited for length.","slide10":"I feel wicked sleeping in a warm bed, while somewhere out there my dearest friends are dropping from exhaustion or being knocked to the ground.","slide11":"I feel like a songbird whose wings have been ripped off and who keeps hurling itself against the bars of its dark cage.","slide12":"Saturday, 15 July, 1944 Yet, I still believe, in spite of everything, that people are truly good at heart.","slide13":"On August 4, 1944, the SS stormed the secret annex and deported all occupants. Anne died in the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp at the age of 15.","slide2":"Writing in a diary is a really strange experience for someone like me.","slide3":"It seems to me that later on neither I nor anyone else will be interested in the musings of a thirteen-year-old schoolgirl.","slide4":"After May 1940 the good times were few and far between.","slide5":"Hiding… where would we hide? In the city? In the country? In a house? In a shack? When, where, how …?","slide6":"Moortje, my cat, was the only living creature I said goodbye to.","slide7":"The hiding place was located in Father’s office building.","slide8":"At eight o’clock the doorbell suddenly rang. All I could think of was that someone was coming to get us, you know who I mean.","slide9":"Our many Jewish friends and acquaintances are being taken away in droves."}